
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `du` baraye mohasebeye hajme disk-i ke file-ha va directory-ha estefade mikonand, be kar miravad. Yani be shoma neshon mide har file ya directory cheghadr ja gerefte ast.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `du -h`  --> 📏  Hajm-ha ra be shekle ghabl-khani neshon mide (mesle KB, MB, GB).
    🔹 `du -s`  --> 📦  Faghat koll hajme directory ra neshon mide, na etela’at-e har file dakhelash ra.
    🔹 `du -a`  --> 📄  Hajme hameye file-ha va directory-ha ra neshon mide.
    🔹 `du -m`  --> 💾  Hajm ra be megabyte (MB) neshon mide.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ du
    
    🔹 Namayesh hajme disk-e directory-e فعلی va zir-directory-ha.

    $ du -h *
    
    🔹 Namayesh hajme ghabl-khani hameye file-ha va directory-ha dar directory-e فعلی.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ du -sh documents
   
    🔹 Koll-e hajm-e directory-e "documents" ra be shekle ghabl-khani neshon mide.  Be jaye neshon dadan hajm-e har file va directory dakhel "documents", faghat koll-e hajm ra neshon mide.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `du` command is used to estimate file and directory space usage. It shows how much disk space each file and directory is taking up.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `du -h`  --> 📏  Display sizes in a human-readable format (e.g., KB, MB, GB).
    🔹 `du -s`  --> 📦  Display only a total for each argument.
    🔹 `du -a`  --> 📄  Display an entry for each file in the directory.
    🔹 `du -m`  --> 💾  Display sizes in megabytes (MB).

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ du
    
    🔹 Display disk space usage of the current directory and its subdirectories.

    $ du -h *
    
    🔹 Display human-readable sizes of all files and directories in the current directory.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ du -sh documents
    
    🔹 Display the total size of the "documents" directory in human-readable format. Instead of showing the size of each file and directory inside "documents", it shows just the total size.
